</div>
</div></div> <hr aria-hidden="true" class="list-divider separator default" data-v-7036083a> <div id="footnotes-list" class="circle-list"><h2>Footnotes</h2>  <div data-type="fulltextNote" id="fn1" class="circle-list__item"><!----> <div class="circle-list__item__indicator"><!----></div> <div class="circle-list__item__grouped"><div class="circle-list__item__grouped__content">

<p class="p"><span class="label">
<sup class="sup">1</sup></span> This definition integrates elements from criminal and rebel governance (Arjona, Kasfir, and Mampilly <a class="xref bibr" href="#r6"><span class="show-for-sr">Reference Arjona, Kasfir and Mampilly</span>2015</a>; Lessing <a class="xref bibr" href="#r56"><span class="show-for-sr">Reference Lessing</span>2021</a>).</p>
</div></div></div><div data-type="fulltextNote" id="fn2" class="circle-list__item"><!----> <div class="circle-list__item__indicator"><!----></div> <div class="circle-list__item__grouped"><div class="circle-list__item__grouped__content">

<p class="p"><span class="label">
<sup class="sup">2</sup></span> In this study, the economic crisis comes from the COVID-19 pandemic, though the theory could apply to other types of shocks.</p>
</div></div></div><div data-type="fulltextNote" id="fn3" class="circle-list__item"><!----> <div class="circle-list__item__indicator"><!----></div> <div class="circle-list__item__grouped"><div class="circle-list__item__grouped__content">

<p class="p"><span class="label">
<sup class="sup">3</sup></span> Although the resource mobilization theory considers a broad range of financial, material, human, organizational, and cultural resources (McCarthy and Zald <a class="xref bibr" href="#r66"><span class="show-for-sr">Reference McCarthy and Zald</span>1977</a>), we focus on financial resources as income.</p>
</div></div></div><div data-type="fulltextNote" id="fn4" class="circle-list__item"><!----> <div class="circle-list__item__indicator"><!----></div> <div class="circle-list__item__grouped"><div class="circle-list__item__grouped__content">

<p class="p"><span class="label">
<sup class="sup">4</sup></span> We recognize that the lack of economic opportunities may give no alternative to some individuals but to engage in illicit activities (Sviatschi <a class="xref bibr" href="#r86"><span class="show-for-sr">Reference Sviatschi</span>2022</a>).</p>
</div></div></div><div data-type="fulltextNote" id="fn5" class="circle-list__item"><!----> <div class="circle-list__item__indicator"><!----></div> <div class="circle-list__item__grouped"><div class="circle-list__item__grouped__content">

<p class="p"><span class="label">
<sup class="sup">5</sup></span> Territorially embedded criminals (e.g., <em class="italic">clicas</em> at the street level) may not “choose” rationally the territories they occupy. However, they can choose the kind of relationship they have with their communities.</p>
</div></div></div><div data-type="fulltextNote" id="fn6" class="circle-list__item"><!----> <div class="circle-list__item__indicator"><!----></div> <div class="circle-list__item__grouped"><div class="circle-list__item__grouped__content">

<p class="p"><span class="label">
<sup class="sup">6</sup></span> Maslow’s (<a class="xref bibr" href="#r65"><span class="show-for-sr">Reference Maslow</span>1943</a>) pyramid includes physiological needs (food and shelter) at the bottom, followed by security (safety and protection), love (affection, belonging, and family), esteem (self-esteem and status), and self-actualization (self-fulfillment) at the top.</p>
</div></div></div><div data-type="fulltextNote" id="fn7" class="circle-list__item"><!----> <div class="circle-list__item__indicator"><!----></div> <div class="circle-list__item__grouped"><div class="circle-list__item__grouped__content">

<p class="p"><span class="label">
<sup class="sup">7</sup></span> There could be other higher-order needs motivating requests for criminal help, such as safety, belonging, or status (Sharkey et al. <a class="xref bibr" href="#r81"><span class="show-for-sr">Reference Sharkey, Shekhtmeyster, Chavez-Lopez, Norris and Sass</span>2011</a>), but we focus on physiological needs as they take priority in being procured.</p>
</div></div></div><div data-type="fulltextNote" id="fn8" class="circle-list__item"><!----> <div class="circle-list__item__indicator"><!----></div> <div class="circle-list__item__grouped"><div class="circle-list__item__grouped__content">

<p class="p"><span class="label">
<sup class="sup">8</sup></span> The concurrence of criminals providing aid in locations where the state also assists the population is observationally equivalent to hybrid governance (Arias <a class="xref bibr" href="#r3"><span class="show-for-sr">Reference Arias</span>2017</a>) or cooperation (Barnes <a class="xref bibr" href="#r11"><span class="show-for-sr">Reference Barnes</span>2017</a>) situations, but the theory emphasizes the competitive motivation of criminal groups to do so.</p>
</div></div></div><div data-type="fulltextNote" id="fn9" class="circle-list__item"><!----> <div class="circle-list__item__indicator"><!----></div> <div class="circle-list__item__grouped"><div class="circle-list__item__grouped__content">

<p class="p"><span class="label">
<sup class="sup">9</sup></span> The relative cost of aid depends on the severity of the economic crisis and the different economic capacities of criminal groups.</p>
</div></div></div><div data-type="fulltextNote" id="fn10" class="circle-list__item"><!----> <div class="circle-list__item__indicator"><!----></div> <div class="circle-list__item__grouped"><div class="circle-list__item__grouped__content">

<p class="p"><span class="label">
<sup class="sup">10</sup></span> Criminals need to balance the coercion they impose on the population. Criminals may try to undermine civilian resistance capacity using mild coercion (threats or lockdowns) while refraining from large-scale violence against civilians that could trigger broad community resistance or law enforcement.</p>
</div></div></div><div data-type="fulltextNote" id="fn11" class="circle-list__item"><!----> <div class="circle-list__item__indicator"><!----></div> <div class="circle-list__item__grouped"><div class="circle-list__item__grouped__content">

<p class="p"><span class="label">
<sup class="sup">11</sup></span> This research design was preregistered in the Open Science Framework (<a class="uri" href="https://osf.io/krzte/">https://osf.io/krzte/</a>) and received IRB approval.</p>
</div></div></div><div data-type="fulltextNote" id="fn12" class="circle-list__item"><!----> <div class="circle-list__item__indicator"><!----></div> <div class="circle-list__item__grouped"><div class="circle-list__item__grouped__content">

<p class="p"><span class="label">
<sup class="sup">12</sup></span> In this operationalization, income captures different respondent characteristics than the economic difficulties index. Here, income is considered an overall measure of relatively stable asset wealth, while the economic difficulties index captures short-term disruptions caused by the pandemic.</p>
</div></div></div><div data-type="fulltextNote" id="fn13" class="circle-list__item"><!----> <div class="circle-list__item__indicator"><!----></div> <div class="circle-list__item__grouped"><div class="circle-list__item__grouped__content">

<p class="p"><span class="label">
<sup class="sup">13</sup></span> Contrary to the intrinsic risks of being perceived as a potential collaborator of a criminal group, asking individuals about their demand for criminal aid or being targets of criminal lockdowns may be primarily associated with the stigmas of poverty or victimization (Moon and Treviño-Rangel <a class="xref bibr" href="#r70"><span class="show-for-sr">Reference Moon and Treviño-Rangel</span>2020</a>), respectively.</p>
</div></div></div></div> <hr aria-hidden="true" class="list-divider separator default" data-v-7036083a> <div id="references-list" class="circle-list"><h2>References</h2> <div id="reference-header-wy7tk" aria-flowto="reference-1-content reference-1-button"><h4>
      REFERENCES
